Where Hit Rate is the same as the True Positive Rate, and the False Alarm Rate is the same as the False Positive Rate.

We aligned the labels across test sessions because cluster index labels are randomly assigned during the clustering process above. We performed this alignment using a “greedy” (sequential) approach. We first calculated the average feature vector for each cluster from two sessions and computed the cosine similarity between each pair. Cluster labels were then reordered to maximize the summed cosine similarity. The three clusters were then merged across sessions, and the resulting clusters were compared to the next session. This process was repeated, comparing the merged set of clusters to a new session, until all sessions were aligned.


Cos(θA,B)=A→⋅B→‖A→‖‖B→‖Summed Cosine Similarity=∑i,jCos(θi,j)∀i≠j,i,j∈Cluster index
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{aligned} & \operatorname{Cos}\left(\theta_{A, B}\right)=\frac{\vec{A} \cdot \vec{B}}{\|\vec{A}\|\|\vec{B}\|} \\ & \text { Summed Cosine Similarity }=\sum_{i, j} \operatorname{Cos}\left(\theta_{i, j}\right) \forall i \neq j, \quad i, j \in \text { Cluster index }\end{aligned}$$\end{document}

We reasoned that if gapes and no movements were driving state changes, then removing them would significantly increase the similarity of subsequent states, making state transitions more difficult to infer. To perform this calculation, we used the mean occurrence probabilities of behaviors in each state inferred by the changepoint model, defined as follows:
p→∼Dirichlet(α→),α∈[0,inf) \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \vec{p} \sim \operatorname{Dirichlet}(\vec{\alpha}), \alpha \in[0, \inf )$$\end{document}
As a measure of dissimilarity, we calculated the L2 norm of the difference in probability vectors between subsequent states.
|Δp→||=||p→s−p→s+1‖2:s∈{0,1}as there is a total of 3 states \begin{document}$$\displaystyle |\overrightarrow{\Delta p}|\left|=| | \vec{p}_{s}-\vec{p}_{s+1} \|_{2}: s \in\{0,1\}\right. \text{ as there is a total of 3 states}$$\end{document}
We standardized the distribution of these ‖Δp→∣\begin{document}$\| \overrightarrow{\Delta p} \mid$\end{document} for all behaviors and for only MTMs using the mean norm difference expected by random vectors of corresponding sizes to account for the difference in the dimensionality of the vectors.
